    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:ea9365d0-579f-49ce-b3ef-a393cb9aa685",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 58-year-old man who appears mildly fatigued but generally well groomed, with a guarded posture when upper abdominal discomfort worsens. He is of average build and reports several months of intermittent burning epigastric pain, early satiety, bloating, and occasional nausea, especially after large meals, coffee, or over-the-counter pain relievers for joint aches. He denies hematemesis but recalls one episode of dark stool several weeks ago that resolved on its own. He often presses a hand over the upper abdomen after meals and says the discomfort is worse late at night.\n\nHe works full time as a warehouse supervisor, a physically demanding but stressful job with irregular breaks and frequent skipped meals. {patientName} typically drinks strong coffee in the morning, eats lunch quickly or not at all, and often has a late dinner. He drinks alcohol socially, usually 1 to 2 beers on most evenings, and has a long history of intermittent NSAID use for chronic knee and low back pain. He quit smoking in his early 40s after an estimated 15 pack-year history.\n\nOutside work, {patientName} enjoys fishing, watching baseball, and spending time with his wife, adult daughter, and a few longtime friends. He generally considers himself resilient and tends to minimize symptoms, which contributed to delayed medical evaluation. His sleep has become less restful because lying down after late meals can trigger reflux-like upper abdominal discomfort.\n\nHe remains independent in all activities of daily living and continues to work, though he has recently started avoiding spicy foods, large meals, and late-night snacks because they worsen his symptoms. He is concerned that stress, alcohol, and pain medicines may be contributing to his stomach problems and is open to lifestyle changes."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:7b3cbb5b-55fa-4e1c-91f2-3a99a5b67aa1",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has a history of chronic bilateral knee osteoarthritis and mechanical low back pain, for which he has used ibuprofen intermittently for years, often several times per week during physically demanding work periods. He also has essential hypertension and hyperlipidemia managed in primary care. He has no known history of peptic ulcer disease, cirrhosis, inflammatory bowel disease, or gastrointestinal cancer. He has never required hospitalization for a prior gastrointestinal bleed.\n\nOver the last 4 to 6 months, {patientName} has experienced progressively more frequent upper abdominal burning discomfort, worsened by coffee, alcohol, and NSAID use, accompanied by bloating and early satiety. He reports occasional nausea without persistent vomiting. His appetite has declined slightly, and he has unintentionally lost about 3 kg over several months because eating has become uncomfortable. He describes one episode of black, tarry stool about 3 weeks ago but did not seek care at the time.\n\nPast medical history includes hypertension, hyperlipidemia, osteoarthritis, and seasonal allergic rhinitis. He underwent screening colonoscopy at age 55 with removal of a small benign polyp. He stopped smoking about 16 years ago and does not use illicit drugs. He drinks alcohol regularly but denies heavy binge drinking. He has had no prior abdominal surgery."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
